[1] Co-circulation of influenza virus types (A and B) and type A subtypes (H1 and H3) in Kathmandu, Nepal
Date: Wed 17 Jan 2018
From: Sher Bahadur Pun <drsherbdr@yahoo.com> [edited]


Over the past few days, there have been an increasing number of patients presenting with influenza like illness (ILI) to Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital (OPD), Kathmandu. Patients have contracted influenza type A (subtypes H1 and H3) and type B. Interestingly, most of the patients were found to be infected with influenza B viruses. However, so far government laboratory does not further elaborate influenza B viruses to identify its lineages, i.e. Yamagata or Victoria lineage. It is, in fact worth knowing lineages of influenza B, which can be helpful in selecting vaccine candidates for this country.

--
Dr. Sher Bahadur Pun, MD, PhD
Clinical Research Unit,
Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital,
Kathmandu, Nepal.

[ProMED thanks Dr Sher Bahadur Pun for this update on the circulation of influenza viruses based on data from Khatmandu. - Mod.UBA]

******
[2] Fatal Cases from Nepal
Date: Sat 20 Jan 2018 08:08
Source: The Kathmandu Post [edited]
http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2018-01-20/kalikot-flu-kills-5-over-100-infected.html


A total of 5 people have died and more than 100 people have been taken ill due to flu at Khadachakra Municipality-3 and 4 in Kalikot district in the last 2 weeks.

The District Health Office (DHO) said 5 people, including 3 children, died after they were struck down by of flu. According to Dhan Singh Kami, the ward chairman of Khadachakra-4, viral fever has taken the lives of 3 children all under the age of one in 2 weeks. At Khadachakra-3, flu has led to the deaths of BP and MP. The DHO Chief Dr Kaushal Ali said medical teams have been deployed to the flu-hit areas, including Pachaljharana, Palata, Sannitribeni, Naraharinath and Tilgufa.

